/// section bg:dark text:light
h5: OPEN SOURCE · TYPESCRIPT · GO
h1: Stream events without the boilerplate.
p: Fluxline is a lightweight SDK for publishing, subscribing to, and replaying ordered event streams. Works with your existing message broker — no new infrastructure required.

////
  html: <pre><code>import { Fluxline } from 'fluxline'

const client = new Fluxline({ brokerUrl: process.env.BROKER_URL })
await client.publish('orders', { id: 'ord_01', total: 49.00 })</code></pre>

col:
  button: Get started -> /docs
  btn-secondary: View on GitHub -> https://github.com

col:
  p: v1.4.2 · 2.1 kB gzipped · Zero runtime dependencies

/// section
h2: Why Fluxline

col:
  icon: bi bi-lightning-charge
  h3: Under 3 kB
  p: The TypeScript client ships at 2.1 kB gzipped. The Go client is a single file you can vendor.

col:
  icon: bi bi-arrow-repeat
  h3: Replay from any offset
  p: Seek back to any sequence number and replay events forward. Works with Kafka, NATS, and Redis Streams.

col:
  icon: bi bi-shield-check
  h3: Exactly-once delivery
  p: Idempotent producer IDs and consumer group offsets give you strong delivery guarantees out of the box.

/// section bg:primary-subtle
h2: Framework integrations

col:
  h3: Next.js / Remix
  p: Server action helpers and route handler bindings. Automatically infer event types from your Zod schemas.

col:
  h3: Hono & Fastify
  p: Middleware that turns any route into an event source. Streaming responses with backpressure handling.

col:
  h3: Go net/http
  p: Handler adapter for standard Go HTTP servers. No generics gymnastics — just plain functions.


